\section{Multiple Choice}

Multiple-choice questions carry the prompt, the offered options, and whether
the form should use radio buttons or checkboxes.  We require at least one
option so the later rendering and counting logic can rely on the list being
non-empty.  The [[next]] flag is the sequence-navigation toggle that every
question type shares: when it is true (the default), the server renders a
\enquote{Next $\rightarrow$} link after the question so respondents can move on
without scanning another QR code.  It is purely presentation, so
[[canonical_dict]] drops it before the hash is computed and editing the value
between rebuilds never orphans the recorded answers.

The [[results]] flag is the second presentation field every question type
shares, and unlike [[next]] it is a tri-state.  [[None]] (the default)
leaves the decision about showing live results to respondents with the
server's global [[--results]] flag; [[True]] and [[False]] override that
flag for this question alone.  The override lets a lecturer keep one
poll's tally hidden until everyone has answered --- avoiding the
bandwagon effect of a visible majority --- while the rest of the deck
still shows live results.  Like [[next]] it never enters the hash, so
flipping it between rebuilds keeps the URL prefix and the collected
answers.

<<classes>>=
@dataclass(frozen=True)
class MCQuestion:
    """A multiple-choice question."""

    text: str
    options: tuple[str, ...]
    multi: bool = False
    next: bool = True
    results: bool | None = None
    kind: str = "mc"

    def __post_init__(self):
        if not self.options:
            raise ValueError("multiple-choice questions need options")

    def to_dict(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
        """Return a JSON-friendly representation of the question."""

        result = {
            "kind": self.kind,
            "text": self.text,
            "options": list(self.options),
            "multi": self.multi,
            "next": self.next,
            "results": self.results,
        }
        return result

    def canonical_dict(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
        """Return the identity-only shape used by ``question_hash``."""

        result = self.to_dict()
        result.pop("next", None)
        result.pop("results", None)
        return result
@

Let's verify that the constructor rejects the degenerate case with no options:

<<test functions>>=
def test_mc_question_requires_options():
    with pytest.raises(ValueError):
        MCQuestion("Which one?", ())
