\subsection{Serialisation}

The persistence shape records every question-owned field explicitly.  That lets
the store treat any extra stored key as store-owned metadata during refresh.
[[canonical_dict]] still strips the presentation-only [[next]] and [[results]]
flags and omits an unset [[fence]] so the hash of historical open questions
stays byte-for-byte stable.

<<open question methods>>=
def to_dict(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
    """Return a JSON-friendly representation of the question."""

    result = {
        "kind": self.kind,
        "text": self.text,
        "max_chars": self.max_chars,
        "fence": self.fence,
        "next": self.next,
        "results": self.results,
    }
    return result

def canonical_dict(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
    """Return the identity-only shape used by ``question_hash``."""

    result = self.to_dict()
    result.pop("next", None)
    result.pop("results", None)
    if result["fence"] is None:
        result.pop("fence")
    return result
@

The limit validation is small, but it is what protects the rest of the system
from impossible forms:

