\section{Ranking Questions}

A ranking question hands the respondent a set of items and asks for an
order rather than a single pick.  It is the multiple-choice family seen
from a different angle: where [[MCQuestion]] with [[multi]] records an
\emph{unordered} set of chosen option indices, a ranking records an
\emph{ordered} list of them.  We reuse that representation deliberately
--- an answer is a list of option indices, best first, so the position
in the list \emph{is} the assigned rank.  Nothing in the store or the
JSON layer has to learn a new shape; the only new logic is validating
that the list is a (partial) permutation and aggregating it into mean
ranks.

The one genuinely new field is [[top_n]].  Leaving it [[None]] asks for a
full ordering of every option; setting it to an integer asks only for
that many favourites, which keeps a long option list approachable.  Both
the form and the answer recorder treat [[top_n]] as a hard cap on how
many ranks a respondent may assign, so --- like the option set itself ---
it shapes the input contract and must enter the canonical identity.  Only
the shared [[next]] and [[results]] flags are presentation.

<<classes>>=
@dataclass(frozen=True)
class RankingQuestion:
    """A question that asks respondents to order a set of items.

    An answer is an ordered list of option indices, best first, so each
    item's position in the list is its assigned rank.  ``top_n`` caps how
    many items a respondent ranks: ``None`` asks for a full ordering of
    every option, while an integer asks for only that many favourites.
    Like the option set, ``top_n`` shapes the input contract, so it is
    part of the canonical identity; only ``next`` and ``results`` are
    presentation.
    """

    text: str
    options: tuple[str, ...]
    top_n: int | None = None
    next: bool = True
    results: bool | None = None
    kind: str = "ranking"

    <<ranking question methods>>
