\section{Pin Questions}

A pin question asks respondents to \emph{point} at something: the form
shows a target --- an image, or a rendered piece of text such as a code
example --- and every click drops a pin.  The lecturer's results page
overlays everyone's pins on the same target, so a prompt like
\enquote{pin the keyword that causes the bug} turns into a visible
cluster over the offending token.

Pins are stored as coordinates normalised to the rendered target:
$x/\mathit{width}$ and $y/\mathit{height}$, both in $[0, 1]$.  Pixel
coordinates would tie an answer to the respondent's screen --- a phone
and a projector render the same image at different sizes, so the
lecturer's overlay would only line up for respondents with the same
device.  Normalising makes a pin a statement about the \emph{content},
which is the only thing all participants share.  An answer is a list of
pin mappings, each with [[x]] and [[y]] and, when the question allows
it, a short [[comment]].

Two question types share this contract.  [[PinImageQuestion]] targets an
image; [[PinTextQuestion]] targets a piece of text.  Everything about
\emph{answering} --- the coordinate shape, the pin cap, the optional
comments --- is identical, so the store and the server dispatch on a
shared tuple rather than duplicating per-type logic.

\subsection{The shared pin contract}

Both [[max_pins]] and [[allow_comment]] shape what a respondent is asked
to produce, so --- like ranking's [[top_n]] --- they belong to the
canonical identity rather than presentation.  The cap on [[max_pins]]
also bounds work downstream: the form renders one hidden input pair per
possible pin and the server's answer parser loops over the same range,
so an unbounded cap would let a single question inflate every request.
The comment cap matches the default [[max_chars]] of open and word-cloud
questions; it is a module constant rather than a per-question field
because varying it would complicate identity for no authoring benefit.

