\subsection{Sniffing image bytes}

The server later serves registered image bytes back to respondents, so
the question model fixes \emph{what counts as an image} once, here,
where both the authoring side and the serving side can import it.  We
recognise a closed allowlist of raster formats by their magic bytes
instead of trusting a file extension or a client-supplied content type:
the bytes are the only input we actually store, so they are the only
thing worth deciding on.  SVG is deliberately absent --- it is an XML
document that may carry scripts, and the served image ends up rendered
in every respondent's browser.  Sniffing is prefix-only by design: it
gatekeeps the content type for serving, not image integrity, and a
truncated PNG fails harmlessly in the browser rather than in mentipy.

<<constants>>=
RASTER_IMAGE_MAGIC = (
    (b"\x89PNG\r\n\x1a\n", "image/png"),
    (b"\xff\xd8\xff", "image/jpeg"),
    (b"GIF87a", "image/gif"),
    (b"GIF89a", "image/gif"),
)
RASTER_IMAGE_MIMES = frozenset(
    mime for _, mime in RASTER_IMAGE_MAGIC
) | {"image/webp"}
@

WebP does not fit the simple prefix table: its container is RIFF, whose
magic carries a length field at bytes 4--8, so we match the format tag
at bytes 8--12 separately.

<<functions>>=
def sniff_image_mime(data: bytes) -> str | None:
    """Return the MIME type of raster image bytes, or ``None``.

    Recognises PNG, JPEG, GIF and WebP by their magic bytes.  SVG is
    deliberately not recognised: it can carry scripts, so it is not
    safe to serve back to respondents.
    """

    for magic, mime in RASTER_IMAGE_MAGIC:
        if data.startswith(magic):
            return mime
    if data[:4] == b"RIFF" and data[8:12] == b"WEBP":
        return "image/webp"
    return None
@

The sniffer must accept each allowlisted format and reject SVG even
when the markup is well-formed --- rejecting it here is the security
boundary, not a formatting nicety.

<<test functions>>=

PNG_SAMPLE = b"\x89PNG\r\n\x1a\n" + b"\x00" * 8


def test_sniff_image_mime_detects_raster_and_rejects_svg():
    assert sniff_image_mime(PNG_SAMPLE) == "image/png"
    assert sniff_image_mime(b"\xff\xd8\xff\xe0rest") == "image/jpeg"
    assert sniff_image_mime(b"GIF89a;") == "image/gif"
    assert (
        sniff_image_mime(b"RIFF\x00\x00\x00\x00WEBPVP8 ")
        == "image/webp"
    )
    assert sniff_image_mime(b"<svg xmlns='...'></svg>") is None
    assert sniff_image_mime(b"") is None
@

\subsection{Pin-on-image}

The identity question for an image target is: \emph{which} image?  The
answer must be the image \emph{bytes}, not the path.  A path changes
when the lecturer recompiles the same slides from a different checkout
or renames a figure directory, and tying the hash to it would orphan the
collected answers on every such non-change.  Hashing the bytes mirrors
how every other question type digests its full input contract --- two
slides showing the same picture are the same poll.

That choice creates a construction problem: [[question_from_dict]] must
rebuild a stored question from JSON alone, with no filesystem in sight.
The dataclass therefore carries the digest and the sniffed MIME type as
plain string fields, and only the [[from_image_bytes]] classmethod ever
touches raw bytes.  The original [[image_path]] is kept as a
presentation field because the LaTeX renderer still needs something to
hand to [[\includegraphics]]; it never enters the hash.

<<classes>>=
