\subsection{Pin-on-text}

The text variant exists because the most natural pin targets in a
lecture are often not figures but \emph{rendered text}: a code example
where students should pin the faulty keyword, a paragraph where they
should pin the weakest claim.  The content is a single raw string ---
deliberately not markdown, because the same content must also render on
the LaTeX slide, and a markdown-to-LaTeX translation would make the two
surfaces drift.  Instead the authoring call labels the string with a
[[language]]: a Pygments lexer name renders it as highlighted code on
the web and as a [[minted]] listing on the slide, [[None]] renders it
as prose, and the special value [[latex]] means the string \emph{is}
LaTeX --- the slide typesets it natively and the authoring helper
caches a pandoc-converted HTML rendering in [[content_html]] so the
stdlib server never needs pandoc installed.

For identity the same reasoning as the image applies: the content
string is the contract, so it is hashed; [[language]] and
[[content_html]] only change how the same string is displayed, so ---
like a word cloud's visualisation fields --- they stay out of the hash
and retagging a snippet keeps its URL and answer pool.

