\section{Canonicalisation}

The rest of the system works on a question union.  The helper that rebuilds a
question from stored JSON is the bridge between the typed model and the JSON
registry.

<<classes>>=
Question = (
    MCQuestion
    | OpenQuestion
    | ScaleQuestion
    | WordCloudQuestion
    | RankingQuestion
    | PinImageQuestion
    | PinTextQuestion
)
@

\subsection{Rebuilding stored questions}

The dispatcher reads the stored [[kind]] once, then hands each variant to the
constructor that enforces that variant's invariants.  Unknown kinds fail loudly:
guessing would make corrupted or future store files look valid.

<<functions>>=
def question_from_dict(data: Mapping[str, Any]) -> Question:
    """Rebuild a question object from stored JSON data."""

    kind = data["kind"]

    <<rebuild stored multiple-choice question>>
    <<rebuild stored open question>>
    <<rebuild stored scale question>>
    <<rebuild stored wordcloud question>>
    <<rebuild stored ranking question>>
    <<rebuild stored pin-image question>>
    <<rebuild stored pin-text question>>

    raise ValueError(f"unknown question kind: {kind}")
@

Multiple-choice options are stored as JSON arrays, but the frozen dataclass uses
a tuple so callers cannot mutate a registered question after hashing it.

<<rebuild stored multiple-choice question>>=
if kind == "mc":
    return MCQuestion(
        text=str(data["text"]),
        options=tuple(data["options"]),
        multi=bool(data.get("multi", False)),
        next=bool(data.get("next", True)),
        <<rebuild stored [[results]] override>>
    )
@

The tri-state [[results]] override is read the same way for every kind:
an absent or [[null]] key stays [[None]] --- deferring to the server's
global flag --- rather than being coerced to [[False]], which would
silently lock every legacy question out of public results.

<<rebuild stored [[results]] override>>=
results=(
    None if data.get("results") is None else bool(data["results"])
),
@

Stored JSON is less typed than the in-memory dataclasses.  We therefore coerce
[[fence]] back to [[str]] when it is present so older or hand-edited store files
still rebuild into the same [[OpenQuestion]] shape as freshly rendered
questions.

<<rebuild stored open question>>=
if kind == "open":
    return OpenQuestion(
        text=str(data["text"]),
        max_chars=int(data.get("max_chars", 280)),
        fence=None if data.get("fence") is None else str(data["fence"]),
        next=bool(data.get("next", True)),
        <<rebuild stored [[results]] override>>
    )
@

Scale reconstruction keeps default bounds and labels here rather than in the
store so old records inherit the same defaults as newly authored questions.

<<rebuild stored scale question>>=
if kind == "scale":
    return ScaleQuestion(
        text=str(data["text"]),
        low=int(data.get("low", 1)),
        high=int(data.get("high", 5)),
        low_label=str(data.get("low_label", "")),
        high_label=str(data.get("high_label", "")),
        next=bool(data.get("next", True)),
        <<rebuild stored [[results]] override>>
    )
@

Word-cloud reconstruction coerces [[extra_stop_words]] back to a tuple
because JSON only knows lists --- a list would break the frozen
dataclass's hashability the next time the question takes part in a set
or dictionary key.  Every presentation field also falls back to its
class-level default if a hand-edited or older store file omits it.

<<rebuild stored wordcloud question>>=
if kind == "wordcloud":
    return WordCloudQuestion(
        text=str(data["text"]),
        max_chars=int(data.get("max_chars", 280)),
        split_words=bool(data.get("split_words", True)),
        min_word_length=int(data.get("min_word_length", 3)),
        extra_stop_words=tuple(data.get("extra_stop_words", ())),
        use_default_stopwords=bool(
            data.get("use_default_stopwords", True)
        ),
        render=str(data.get("render", "svg")),
        next=bool(data.get("next", True)),
        <<rebuild stored [[results]] override>>
    )
@

Ranking reconstruction coerces [[options]] back to a tuple for the same
reason multiple-choice does --- a list would make the frozen dataclass
unhashable.  [[top_n]] is read with [[None]] as its fallback so an older
or hand-edited store entry that omits it rebuilds as a full ordering, the
same default the constructor uses.

<<rebuild stored ranking question>>=
if kind == "ranking":
    stored_top_n = data.get("top_n")
    return RankingQuestion(
        text=str(data["text"]),
        options=tuple(data["options"]),
        top_n=None if stored_top_n is None else int(stored_top_n),
        next=bool(data.get("next", True)),
        <<rebuild stored [[results]] override>>
    )
@

Pin-image reconstruction is the payoff of storing the digest instead of
re-deriving it: rebuilding never opens the image file, so a store copied
to another machine still serves and aggregates correctly.  The MIME
fallback only matters for hand-edited entries; anything written by
[[from_image_bytes]] carries an explicit sniffed type.

<<rebuild stored pin-image question>>=
if kind == "pinimage":
    stored_path = data.get("image_path")
    return PinImageQuestion(
        text=str(data["text"]),
        image_sha256=str(data["image_sha256"]),
        image_mime=str(data.get("image_mime", "image/png")),
        image_path=None if stored_path is None else str(stored_path),
        max_pins=int(data.get("max_pins", 1)),
        allow_comment=bool(data.get("allow_comment", False)),
        next=bool(data.get("next", True)),
        <<rebuild stored [[results]] override>>
    )
@

Pin-text reconstruction keeps the two optional presentation strings
nullable rather than coercing [[None]] to [["None"]], which would
otherwise silently turn a prose target into code highlighted with a
nonsense lexer.

<<rebuild stored pin-text question>>=
if kind == "pintext":
    stored_language = data.get("language")
    stored_html = data.get("content_html")
    return PinTextQuestion(
        text=str(data["text"]),
        content=str(data["content"]),
        language=(
            None if stored_language is None else str(stored_language)
        ),
        content_html=None if stored_html is None else str(stored_html),
        max_pins=int(data.get("max_pins", 1)),
        allow_comment=bool(data.get("allow_comment", False)),
        next=bool(data.get("next", True)),
        <<rebuild stored [[results]] override>>
    )
@

