\subsection{Hashing canonical JSON}

The canonical hash uses sorted JSON keys so that it depends on the meaning of
the question, not on the incidental order in which Python produced a mapping.

Every question type now exposes a [[canonical_dict]] method that returns the
identity-only payload.  For multiple-choice and scale questions the identity is
the whole persistence shape minus the shared presentation flags ([[next]] and
[[results]]).  Open questions do the
same and additionally drop an unset [[fence]] so historical hashes stay
byte-for-byte stable even though [[to_dict]] now records explicit defaults.
Word clouds additionally strip their visualisation fields, keeping existing
answer logs bound to the same URL prefix while presentation evolves.  Ranking
questions are the mirror image of that choice: their identity keeps the ordered
option set and the [[top_n]] cap, because both shape what the respondent is
asked to order, and only [[next]] is dropped.  Pin questions combine both
stances: the target content (the image byte digest, the raw text string)
and the pin contract ([[max_pins]], [[allow_comment]]) are identity, while
the rendering hints ([[image_path]], [[image_mime]], [[language]],
[[content_html]]) follow the word-cloud rule and stay out of the hash.

<<functions>>=
def question_hash(question: Question) -> str:
    """Return the full SHA-256 digest for ``question``."""

    canonical_payload = question.canonical_dict()
    payload = json.dumps(
        canonical_payload,
        ensure_ascii=False,
        separators=(",", ":"),
        sort_keys=True,
    )
    return hashlib.sha256(payload.encode("utf-8")).hexdigest()
@

The hash is the stable identity of a question.  We therefore pin both the happy
path and a nearby change that must alter the digest.

<<test functions>>=
def test_question_hash_is_stable_for_identical_questions():
    first = MCQuestion("How was it?", ("Great", "OK", "Boring"))
    second = MCQuestion("How was it?", ("Great", "OK", "Boring"))

    digest = question_hash(first)

    assert digest == question_hash(second)
    assert re.fullmatch(r"[0-9a-f]{64}", digest)
@

Changing the option order changes the meaning of a poll, so it must also change
the canonical digest.

